# Pear Shaped Diamond Ring: The Complete {{year}} Settings, Metals & Prices Guide

## TL;DR — Key Facts Before You Shop

- A pear shaped diamond ring ranges from **$1,180** (setting alone, platinum solitaire) to **$4,005+** for pear-specific halo settings on Blue Nile
- Add a 1ct natural pear diamond from **[$3,150](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28393670?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)** — or a 1ct lab pear from around **$1,006** — to complete the ring
- Every Blue Nile setting shown in this guide comes in **platinum, white gold, yellow gold, and rose gold** — metal choice is yours
- The V-prong at the point is non-negotiable — any other prong type risks chipping the tip
- Point-up orientation reads modern and editorial; point-down orientation reads romantic and traditional — decide before buying the setting
- The pear shape visually elongates the finger more than almost any other diamond cut at the same carat weight

---

A pear shaped diamond ring is not a casual decision. It is the most asymmetrical, orientation-sensitive, setting-dependent shape in the diamond market — and it rewards buyers who understand the rules with a ring that stops conversations.

Most buyers discover pear diamonds one of three ways: a celebrity engagement announcement, a vintage estate piece, or a side-by-side carat comparison where the pear looks significantly larger than a round at the same weight. All three are valid entry points. None of them prepare you for the actual buying decisions you have to make.

This guide covers all of them. Setting styles, metal types, named-concept frameworks, real Blue Nile prices, and every question a serious buyer asks before placing an order.

---

## What Makes a Pear Shaped Diamond Ring Different From Every Other Shape?

The pear cut — also called a teardrop diamond — is a hybrid brilliant cut with 58 facets. It combines the rounded belly of an oval with the tapered point of a marquise. That asymmetry is its defining feature and its primary challenge.

Every other popular diamond shape is symmetrical. Round, oval, princess, emerald, cushion — you can orient any of them in the setting and the visual result is the same. A pear diamond is different. Point-up reads one way. Point-down reads another. Tilted even slightly reads wrong.

The asymmetry also concentrates stress at the tip. The pointed end of a pear diamond is the single most vulnerable point on any diamond shape in common use. A standard round prong at the tip creates a line of contact that can lever against the facet edge under impact and cause a chip. A V-prong wraps the tip, distributing pressure evenly across the curvature and eliminating that risk.

No setting engineer at a serious jeweler will put a round prong at the tip of a pear diamond. If you see a setting with round prongs at both ends of a pear stone, do not buy it — or demand confirmation that a V-prong will be used at the point before the stone is set.

The bow-tie effect is the third pear-specific concern. Like oval diamonds, pear cuts can show a dark, bow-tie shaped shadow across the center when the crown proportions are wrong. A well-cut pear minimizes the bow-tie to a faint visual texture; a poorly-cut pear turns it into a dead zone that kills the sparkle of the entire center of the ring.

You cannot evaluate bow-tie severity from a GIA certificate. You must watch the 360° HD video on **[Blue Nile's pear diamond search](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-search?shape=pear&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)** and look for consistent light return across the full face of the stone in motion.

---

## The Metal Multiplier Effect: How Your Metal Choice Changes Everything

The Metal Multiplier Effect is the single most underexplained concept in pear diamond ring buying.

Here is what most guides miss: the metal of your setting directly changes the perceived color grade of your pear diamond. This is not a minor visual tweak. It is a difference worth 1–2 color grades in perceived whiteness — and 1–2 color grades on a pear diamond can mean a $1,000–$2,000 price difference on the stone alone.

**How it works:**

Platinum and white gold reflect a cool, neutral white light. When you set a G or H color pear diamond in platinum, the reflected metal light reads as white against the stone. The diamond appears a half-grade to a full grade whiter than its certificate says.

Yellow gold reflects warm, golden light. When you set that same G or H color pear diamond in yellow gold, the reflected light reads as warm — and actually masks yellow tinting in the diamond. A G-H color pear in a yellow gold setting looks nearly as clean as an F in white gold at a fraction of the price.

Rose gold sits between the two. It reflects a soft, warm pink-champagne tone that flatters I-J color pear diamonds particularly well.

**The practical buying decision:**

| Metal | Best Diamond Color | Visual Effect | Budget Move |
|-------|--------------------|---------------|-------------|
| Platinum | D–G | Crisp, icy white | No — buy the best color here |
| White Gold (14k or 18k) | D–H | Clean, white, neutral | Slight — H looks like F |
| Yellow Gold (14k or 18k) | G–I | Warm, romantic, vintage | Yes — I looks like G |
| Rose Gold (14k or 18k) | H–J | Soft, flattering, feminine | Yes — J reads as H |

Every Blue Nile setting in this guide is available in all four metals. Prices shown are for platinum unless noted. White gold and yellow gold versions typically run **$200–$400 less** than the platinum price. Rose gold prices match yellow gold.

Use The Metal Multiplier Effect to buy a better stone for your budget. If you want yellow gold, buy an I color instead of a G — and put that $800 difference toward a higher carat or better cut.

