## The Orientation Decision: Point-Up or Point-Down?

The Orientation Decision is the choice that defines every pear shaped diamond ring — and most buyers make it without realizing there was a choice at all.

**Point-up (modern):** The pointed tip of the pear diamond faces toward the fingernail. This is the editorial orientation. It reads sharp, angular, and contemporary. The rounded belly sits closest to the hand, and the tip extends toward the nail like a directional arrow. Most modern pear diamond rings — including virtually all celebrity pear engagement rings — use point-up orientation.

**Point-down (classic/romantic):** The rounded belly faces the fingernail and the tip points toward the hand. This is the vintage orientation. It reads softer and more traditional. The belly of the pear creates a teardrop silhouette that sits flat against the hand rather than projecting upward.

Neither orientation is objectively better. But here is the practical rule: if your setting has a V-prong at only one end, the V-prong must be at the tip — regardless of which way the tip faces. A setting with a V-prong at the round end is backwards for a pear diamond.

Confirm orientation before the stone is set. Once a pear diamond is set in a specific orientation, the prong configuration is fixed to that direction. Reversing it after setting requires a new setting or resetting the stone in a modified basket.

**How to decide:** Hold a loose pear diamond (or look at 360° video) in each orientation against your hand. The point-up version will look longer and thinner. The point-down version will look slightly wider and more compact. If you want maximum finger-elongation, go point-up. If you want a soft, feminine silhouette, go point-down.

[![Pear shaped diamond ring in yellow gold solitaire setting showing warm metal against white diamond on Blue Nile](/images/pear-shaped-diamond-ring-solitaire-yellow-gold.avif)](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings?MetalType=all&Diamonds=Dia&ShapeID=Pear&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)
