## Pavé and Halo Settings for Pear Shaped Diamond Rings

Pavé settings add micro-set accent diamonds along the shank, which increases the sparkle of the ring dramatically without increasing the center stone size. Halo settings surround the pear diamond with a frame of small round brilliants, making the center stone appear 10–20% larger than its actual carat weight.

Both styles are popular for pear diamonds. Both create specific challenges the buyer needs to understand.

For pavé shanks: the V-prong at the tip of the pear stone must be tall enough to clear the pavé row without creating a gap or a snag point. Low-set pavé that runs into the side of the pear diamond creates a shadow line that looks wrong in photos.

For halo settings: the halo frame must be shaped to the pear outline — not circular or oval. A round halo on a pear diamond creates visual misalignment that looks like a sizing mistake. Ask explicitly for a pear-shaped halo when ordering.

