## Pear Shaped Diamond Ring for Men

Men's pear diamond rings are a niche category with a growing following, particularly in east-west horizontal settings where the diamond sits sideways on the finger rather than point-up or point-down.

The east-west configuration orients the pear so that the long axis runs parallel to the finger rather than perpendicular to it. In a thick, low-profile bezel setting, this creates a confident, architectural look that reads distinctly masculine — more like a signet ring than an engagement ring.

For men's pear diamond rings:
- Bezel settings provide the best protection and most masculine profile
- East-west orientation is more popular in men's jewelry than traditional vertical orientation
- 1.5–2ct+ stones work better proportionally on wider hands
- Platinum or yellow gold with a matte or satin finish reads clean and modern

Blue Nile's standard catalog does not offer a pre-configured men's pear diamond ring. This is typically a custom piece — specify east-west orientation and a bezel or partial-bezel setting when working with any jeweler.

---

## Pear Diamond Pinky Ring

Pear shaped diamond jewelry extends well beyond the engagement ring. Pinky rings, pendants, stacking bands, and right-hand fashion rings all use the pear shape — and the same setting and orientation rules apply across every category.

Pear diamonds in pinky ring configurations have appeared in hip-hop and pop culture jewelry extensively over the past several years. The silhouette reads dramatic even at smaller sizes because the elongated shape on a smaller finger creates strong visual contrast.

For pinky rings:
- 0.50–0.75ct pear diamonds are ideal for US ring sizes 4–5 (typical pinky sizes)
- Bezel or low-set pavé settings protect the stone from the constant side-friction that pinky rings experience
- Point-up orientation is more common for pinky rings — it emphasizes the directional asymmetry

The V-prong requirement is even more critical for pinky ring settings. The pinky finger takes more lateral stress than the ring finger because of constant knocking against adjacent surfaces.

---

## Large Pear Shaped Diamond Ring: 2ct, 3ct, 4ct, and 5ct

At large carat weights, the pear diamond is an event. The 2ct pear at the standard 1.60 L/W ratio covers approximately 11.5mm × 7.5mm of finger — roughly the width of two-thirds of a finger and the length of nearly a full one.

**2ct natural pear diamond:** Starting from approximately $14,500 for a G-VS2 Ideal on Blue Nile. The E-VVS1 in a 2ct natural pear runs $22,610 as seen in the pillar guide — **[complete 2ct pear pricing at the main guide](/pear-cut-diamond)**.

**3ct natural pear diamond:** Enters rare-stone territory. Prices start around $40,000 and escalate rapidly with color and clarity. The 3ct D-FL on Blue Nile runs $93,910. At this weight, the stone is the investment — the setting is secondary.

**4ct and 5ct pear diamonds:** Custom-sourced territory. Blue Nile's standard pear inventory at 4ct+ is limited. Contact a diamond broker or specialty retailer at this weight range. Expect $80,000–$250,000+ depending on color, clarity, and certificate.

**The lab alternative at large sizes:** The price-per-carat gap widens dramatically above 2ct. A 3ct lab pear at D-VVS1 runs approximately $7,000–$9,000 on Blue Nile. The same grade in natural costs $40,000+. The visual and chemical identity is identical. The market resale value is not — but if resale is not a concern, the lab stone at 3ct is one of the strongest value positions in all of diamond retail.

---

## Pear Shaped Diamond Ring vs. Oval Diamond Ring

The pear and the oval are the two dominant elongated brilliant cuts. They are close cousins with significant differences that matter to buyers.

| Factor | Pear Diamond Ring | Oval Diamond Ring |
|--------|------------------|------------------|
| Silhouette | One pointed end, one rounded — asymmetrical | Both ends rounded — symmetrical |
| Finger elongation | Maximum — the point creates a strong upward direction | Very good — the elongated oval reads tall |
| Setting complexity | Higher — V-prong required at tip | Lower — standard prongs work at both ends |
| Orientation sensitivity | High — point-up vs. point-down is a design decision | Low — both orientations look the same |
| Bow-tie risk | Yes — same as oval | Yes — same as pear |
| Finger presence | More dramatic and directional | Softer and more symmetrical |
| Price per carat | Similar to oval at most weights | Similar to pear at most weights |
| Best for | Buyers who want something asymmetrical and bold | Buyers who want elongation with symmetrical balance |

If you are deciding between a pear and an oval for an engagement ring, try both orientations of the pear first. Some buyers who think they want an oval discover they prefer the directionality of the pear; some buyers who think they want a pear prefer the balance of the oval.

**For more on the oval diamond ring:** see the [complete oval shaped diamond ring guide](/oval-cut-diamond).

