## Final Verdict: The Best Pear Shaped Diamond Ring for Every Budget

**Under $5,000 (complete ring):** 1ct lab-grown pear (G-VS2, IGI Ideal) in the Classic Four Prong Solitaire setting in white gold. The lab pear at this specification costs approximately $1,800–$2,500; the setting adds $900–$1,000 in white gold. Total: $2,700–$3,500. This is a genuine, eye-clean, beautiful pear diamond ring that no one can distinguish from a natural diamond in daily wear.

**$5,000–$10,000:** 1ct natural pear (H-VS2, GIA Ideal) in a Petite Cathedral Solitaire or pavé setting in yellow gold. Apply The Metal Multiplier Effect — the H color reads as F against the warm yellow gold. Total setting + stone budget lands at $7,500–$9,500.

**$10,000–$20,000:** 1.25–1.5ct natural pear (G-VS1, GIA) in the Pear Shape Side Stone Diamond Halo by James Allen in platinum. The halo amplifies the visible size, the pear-specific frame is engineered for the shape, and platinum holds the V-prong securely for decades. This is the best pear engagement ring you can build within this budget.

**$20,000+:** Custom-design territory. Work with a certified gemologist to source a 2ct+ GIA-graded pear diamond directly and commission a bespoke setting. Blue Nile's "Design Your Own Ring" tool works at this level too — select the platinum pear halo base and pair it with a 2ct natural pear at your chosen grade.

