## Expert Summary

**What is a pear shaped diamond ring?** A pear shaped diamond ring features a pear cut (teardrop cut) diamond — a 58-facet hybrid brilliant with one rounded end and one pointed end. It is the most asymmetrical of the popular diamond shapes and requires specific setting decisions that other shapes do not.

**Best setting for a pear diamond ring:** Classic Four Prong Solitaire (platinum, $1,180) for minimalists; Pear Shape Side Stone Diamond Halo by James Allen ($3,570–$4,005) for maximum impact. A V-prong at the pointed tip is mandatory in all configurations.

**Key buying frameworks:** (1) The Metal Multiplier Effect — yellow and rose gold mask color tinting, enabling buyers to purchase 1–2 lower color grades at significant savings. (2) The Orientation Decision — confirm point-up vs. point-down before buying the setting; the V-prong configuration is direction-specific.

**Complete pear diamond ring budget:** 1ct lab pear in solitaire = $2,700–$4,500 total. 1ct natural pear in solitaire = $8,000–$12,000 total. 1.5ct natural pear in halo = $20,000–$28,000 total.

**Where to buy:** **[Blue Nile pear diamond rings](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring?shape=pear&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)** — 360° HD video on every stone, all settings available in platinum, white gold, yellow gold, and rose gold.

